<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Layia fremontii </i>is common in heavy soil grasslands of central California and the North Coast Ranges, where it has showy yellow ray flowers that have lobed white tips. It presents an abundance of creamy color in vernally wet grasslands during early spring. <i>Achyrachaena mollis </i>is a common composite of grassy areas of the California Floristic Province, where its papery, shiny white scales atop the disk flowers and fruits are more conspicuous than are the short rays (UCB 2006). <br/>
<br/>
Barbour et al. (2003, 2007b) recognized the <i>Downingia-Lasthenia </i>class for California vernal pool vegetation on all geomorphic surfaces, landscapes, and soil types in the Central Valley and adjacent foothills. Within that class, they recognized this alliance for vegetation of comparative shallow vernal pools and of pool edges. <br/>
<br/>
This alliance has a similar inundation pattern to the <i>Montia fontana-Sidalcea calycosa </i>and <i>Trifolium variegatum </i>alliances and commonly occurs on substrates derived from metamorphic or volcanic material. However, it is not found on basalt flows of table mountains. Some of these stands are just slightly moister than the surrounding uplands and occupy the transition between vernal pools or swales and uplands. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
